## Architecture
- Keep transport, application, domain, and persistence concerns separated.
- Handlers/controllers must stay thin.
- Business logic belongs in services or domain packages.
- Database and external system code belongs behind clear boundaries.
- Avoid framework leakage into core domain logic.

## Package boundaries
- Prefer internal packages for application-private code.
- Use pkg only for intentionally reusable, externally consumable packages.
- Keep package APIs small and cohesive.
- Avoid circular dependencies and package entanglement.

## Construction and wiring
- Prefer explicit dependency injection through constructors.
- Do not use global mutable state for core dependencies.
- Keep initialization in main or dedicated wiring packages.
- Pass concrete dependencies inward; expose narrow interfaces only where a consumer needs them.

## Configuration
- Treat configuration as explicit application input.
- Validate configuration at startup.
- Fail fast on invalid required configuration.
- Never hardcode secrets or environment-specific endpoints.